587. occisam . . . suem. A reference to the crit. note will show how various have been the attempts of successive edd. to impart sense to this passage. Lorenz was the first to perceive that a verse must have dropped out. But even though we pos- tulate a lacuna here, supplying the sentiment which ΒΧ and Lor. supply, no satisfactory sense emerges. For let us suppose the lost verse to have contained words answering in sense to ‘⁶ than this fool Sceledrus''; then the sense of the whole passage would be :—-“ I am quite sure that a slaughtered sow has often more' sense than this blockhead, who is choused into not seeing what he saw.'' But—(1) occisa sus is not among the many types os stupidity in PL, and is not at all likely to be so used; and (2) what is to be done with saepe?
